:::summary
Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart (1756–1791) was the supreme genius of the Classical era in music — a prodigy who began composing at five and performed for European royalty at six, and who in his brief 35 years produced a body of work in every musical genre that represents one of the highest peaks of Western civilization. His operas — *Don Giovanni*, *The Marriage of Figaro*, *The Magic Flute*, *Così fan tutte* — are the central repertoire of opera houses worldwide; his symphonies and piano concertos define the classical forms; his chamber music and sacred works are unsurpassed in their combination of beauty, depth, and technical mastery. Mozart wrote with an ease that his contemporaries found supernatural, yet no music is less superficial: beneath its radiant surface lies an inexhaustible complexity.
:::

